1 — Executive summary
This repository implements a Node.js + Express backend for an assessment and feedback platform. The API supports two primary user flows:
- Authenticated admin/manager/leader flows for creating and managing assessments, question banks, exporting reports, and viewing dashboards.
- Invitation-based employee (no-login) flows that allow invited employees to complete assessments via a secure token link.

Key capabilities:
- User lifecycle (register/login/profile/email verification/password resets).
- Invitation issuance (single and bulk via CSV/Excel) and tokenized employee access.
- Assessment lifecycle: draft, start, submit, review, and export (Excel/PDF).
- Question bank CRUD with bulk upload and template support.
- Role-based dashboards and intelligence endpoints (PDF/Excel exports powered by Puppeteer).
- File uploads (images and Excel), email sending integrations, and a scheduled cron cleanup job.

Primary audience: the next backend engineer or maintainer taking over the project.

------------------------------------------------------------
2 — Architecture & high-level flow
- Entry point: src/index.js — loads environment, connects to MongoDB, conditionally starts server and schedules cron jobs.
- App composition: src/app.js — builds Express app, registers middlewares, mounts versioned routes (/api/v1/*).
- Persistence: MongoDB (mongoose). Models live in src/models/*.model.js.
- Controller pattern: src/controllers/*Controller.js — each controller handles input validation, business logic, and database calls.
- Services: src/services — encapsulate external integrations (email, cloudinary, PDF generation) and complex helper logic.
- Middlewares: src/middlewares — auth, invite flows, file upload handling and role restrictions.
- Exports & heavy operations: some endpoints use Puppeteer to render HTML to PDF, and exceljs/xlsx/json2xls for Excel exports.

Typical request flow (protected admin action):
Client -> Auth middleware (protect) -> Controller -> Models -> Services (email/cloudinary) -> Response

Typical no-login employee flow:
Client (invite link with token) -> employeeAccess middleware (verify token) -> Controller serves assessment -> Submit saves Responses and may mark Invitation as used

------------------------------------------------------------
3 — Tech stack & notable libraries
- Node.js (ES modules) + Express v5
- MongoDB via mongoose
- Authentication: jsonwebtoken (JWT)
- File uploads: multer
- Emails: nodemailer, @sendgrid/mail, or resend (controllers may use different providers; check code)
- PDFs: puppeteer + @sparticuz/chromium, pdf-lib
- Excel/CSV: exceljs, xlsx, csv-parser, json2xls
- Image processing & storage: sharp, cloudinary
- Scheduler: node-cron

Important: package.json uses "type": "module" — import/export syntax (ESM) is used across the codebase.

