4 — Repository layout and key files
Top-level:
- src/
  - config/                  (env loader, constants)
  - db/                      (connectDB, mongoose setup)
  - controllers/             (auth.controller.js, assessment.controller.js, ...)
  - middlewares/             (auth.middleware.js, multer.middleware.js, employee.middleware.js, ...)
  - models/                  (user.model.js, invitation.model.js, question.model.js, response.model.js, ...)
  - routes/                  (auth.routes.js, assessment.routes.js, ...)
  - services/                (email, cloudinary, pdf generation helpers)
  - utils/                   (helpers, validators)
  - app.js                   (Express app builder)
  - index.js                 (entry point, server + cron)
- package.json
- README.md
- Dockerfile
- public/ (static assets)

Files to inspect first:
- src/index.js — server start conditions, cron setup, DB connect behavior
- src/app.js — middleware ordering and route mounting
- src/models/user.model.js — JWT generation and user indexes
- src/middlewares/auth.middleware.js — protect/flexibleProtect/restrictTo behavior
- src/controllers/* — implement business rules and call services

------------------------------------------------------------
5 — Setup & run (detailed)
1) Prerequisites
- Node >= 18 (recommended), npm >= 9
- MongoDB instance (Atlas or local)
- Optional: Cloudinary account, Sendgrid/Resend credentials for email, and a Chromium-compatible environment for Puppeteer when generating PDFs.

2) Local steps
- Copy env template:
  cp .env.example .env
  Fill MONGODB_URL, JWT_SECRET and other provider credentials.

- Install dependencies:
  npm install

- Development server (nodemon + dotenv):
  npm run dev

- Production-like start:
  npm start

- Health check:
  GET http://localhost:8000/ -> { success: true, message: "API is working 🚀" }

3) Notes on serverless (Vercel)
- src/index.js checks process.env.VERCEL — if set, it will NOT call app.listen, and the app is exported for serverless functions.
- Cron and local index cleanup won't run on serverless — separate scheduled workers are required if cron tasks are needed in production.

------------------------------------------------------------
6 — Environment variables (recommended .env.example)
Required/core:
- MONGODB_URL=
- JWT_SECRET=
- PORT=8000
- NODE_ENV=development
Optional / provider specific:
- SENDGRID_API_KEY=
- RESEND_API_KEY=
- SMTP_HOST=, SMTP_PORT=, SMTP_USER=, SMTP_PASS=
- CLOUDINARY_CLOUD_NAME=, CLOUDINARY_API_KEY=, CLOUDINARY_API_SECRET=
- FRONTEND_URL= (CORS origin)
- VERCEL=true (if deploying serverless)

(See Appendix A for a ready .env.example block.)

------------------------------------------------------------
7 — Data models & database notes
All models are defined using mongoose. Core models to be familiar with:
- User: fields include email, password, role, orgName, profile, tokens, verification/reset tokens; method generateAccessToken()
- Invitation: holds invite tokens, email, role, department, expiry and used flags
- Question: question bank records including type (single/multi/scale), metadata, weights
- Assessment / EmployeeAssessment / SubmittedAssessment: assessment instances, persisted snapshots, and responses
- Response: stores answers; used by export endpoints to create Excel/PDF reports

Indexes & important fields:
- invitationToken and reset tokens are indexed for quick lookup
- orgName combined indexes for organization-scoped queries

Data migration considerations:
- Be careful when dropping or altering indexes — src/index.js includes a local index-drop step for invitationId_1 (review before running in prod)

------------------------------------------------------------
8 — Authentication & authorization (details)
- JWT signing: User model provides generateAccessToken which signs JWT with JWT_SECRET and typically expires in ~3h.
- Middleware:
  protect: Bails out if Authorization: Bearer <token> is missing or invalid. Sets req.user = user document.
  flexibleProtect: Tries session JWT (Authorization header or cookie) then falls back to invite token (x-invite-token header or invitation cookie). If invite valid, sets req.guest and req.employee.
  restrictTo(...roles): Use to restrict endpoints to specific roles.
  employeeAccess: Strict invite-mode used for no-login flows.

Security tips:
- Keep JWT_SECRET out of source control.
- Avoid placing invite tokens in URLs for production-sensitive flows — use headers or single-use tokens where possible.
- Add rate-limiting to auth endpoints.

------------------------------------------------------------
9 — Middleware behaviors (practical notes)
- multer.middleware: uses disk storage and writes to os.tmpdir() or /tmp when VERCEL is set. Files should be uploaded to cloud storage after processing and temp files deleted.
- excelUpload: intended for bulk questions/invitations. No size limit configured; monitor memory when parsing large files.
- csvUpload: used by bulk invitation routes — CSV format expected by controller (inspect middleware for precise columns).
- validateImageSize: ensures image uploads meet MIN and MAX bounds (10KB - 4MB).

------------------------------------------------------------
10 — Endpoints (grouped) with short examples
Base path: /api/v1
Auth examples
- POST /auth/register
  Body: { email, password, firstName, lastName, orgName }
- POST /auth/login
  Body: { email, password }
  Response: { token, user }

Invitations
- POST /auth/send-invitation (protected)
  Body: { email, role, orgName, department, expiresAt }
- POST /auth/send-bulk-invitation (protected)
  multipart/form-data: file=bulk.csv

Employee flow (no-login)
- POST /employee-assessment/start
  Header: x-invite-token: <invite-token>
  Response: assessment meta + questions
- POST /employee-assessment/:assessmentId/submit/:token
  Body: { answers: [ { questionId, answer } ] }

Assessment & responses
- POST /assessment/start (protected)
- POST /assessment/:assessmentId/submit (protected)
- POST /responses (flexibleProtect)
- GET /responses/:assessmentId/export (flexibleProtect) -> Excel download

Dashboard & exports
- GET /dashboard/export-pdf (protected) -> triggers Puppeteer render and returns PDF

Notes: For each protected route ensure Authorization header if called as admin. Many endpoints accept flexibleProtect to support both logged-in users and invite-based sessions.

------------------------------------------------------------
11 — File uploads, exports and background work
- Uploads saved to disk (tmp) via multer; controllers should move processed files to cloud storage and remove temp files.
- Excel exports: exceljs and xlsx produce workbooks; large exports should be streamed and offloaded to background jobs to avoid request timeouts.
- PDF exports: puppeteer + @sparticuz/chromium used to run headless chromium in serverless environments. This is resource-heavy — prefer queuing and returning a job URL.

Best practice: implement a job queue (BullMQ / Redis) for heavy tasks (PDF/Excel generation), persist job status and provide download endpoints.

------------------------------------------------------------
12 — Cron & DB maintenance
- src/index.js schedules a cron ('* * * * *') that deletes expired/unverified users every minute. This runs only when index.js is started (not serverless).
- There is code in index.js that attempts to drop an index named invitationId_1 from the assessments collection. This is a local maintenance step and should be reviewed before running in production.

Recommendation: Move scheduled tasks to a separate worker process or external scheduler (e.g., server cron, AWS CloudWatch Events, GitHub Actions scheduled workflow) and guard any destructive DB operations.

------------------------------------------------------------
13 — Deployment notes (Vercel & alternatives)
Vercel considerations:
- App should be exported and not call listen when process.env.VERCEL is set.
- Puppeteer requires a compatible chromium binary; @sparticuz/chromium helps but test in the target environment.
- /tmp is writable on serverless platforms — ensure temp file usage conforms.

Alternative deployments:
- Docker-based deployment on VPS or container platform (DigitalOcean, AWS ECS, Heroku, Render) gives more control for background workers and persistent processes.

------------------------------------------------------------
14 — Testing & QA checklist
- Create Postman or Insomnia collection with environment placeholders:
  - Base URL, JWT_TOKEN, INVITE_TOKEN
- Smoke tests:
  - Register/login as admin
  - Create organization and invitation
  - Start and submit an employee assessment via invite
  - Upload Excel and download exports
- Add automated tests (suggest using Jest + Supertest):
  - Unit tests for utility functions and model methods
  - Integration tests for auth flows and response submit + export
- CI: Add GitHub Actions to run lint and tests on PRs.

------------------------------------------------------------
15 — Onboarding checklist (priority)
1) Pull repo & install: git clone && npm install
2) Copy .env.example -> .env and fill required fields
3) Run dev server: npm run dev and perform health check
4) Register test admin and validate login
5) Create an invitation and run the employee flow
6) Test file uploads and exports locally
7) Inspect controllers to determine which email provider is used in your environment
8) Secure index cleanup code and remove or guard for production
9) Add Postman collection & API.md in repo

------------------------------------------------------------
16 — Troubleshooting - common issues & fixes
- MongoDB connection failures:
  - Ensure MONGODB_URL is correct and network access (firewall/Atlas IP whitelist) is allowed.
  - For SRV errors, check DNS resolution and connection string format.
- Invalid tokens:
  - Ensure JWT_SECRET matches tokens used when issued. Reset tokens if needed.
- Invite token not accepted:
  - Check whether invitation token stored uses field token or token1. employeeAccess checks both.
- Upload failures on Vercel:
  - Ensure code uses /tmp and that the file size limits are respected.
- Timeouts on exports:
  - Offload large exports to background jobs; stream results when possible.

